{"parse":{"title":"car","pageid":4526,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"car\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''Car'''ib,es:'''Car'''ibe}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|2&3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/kɑː/|[kʰɑː]|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-a car.ogg|a=RP|text=a car}}\n* {{IPA|en|[kʰäɾ]|a=Scotland}}\n* {{IPA|en|/kɑɹ/|[kʰɑ̝͗ɹ]|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-car.ogg|a=GA}}\n** {{IPA|en|[kʰaː]|a=Boston}}\n* {{IPA|en|/kaː/|[kʰäː]|a=AU,NZ}}\n* {{IPA|en|/kʰɑɹ/|a=IE}}\n** {{IPA|en|/kʰʲæɹ/|a=[[w: Dublin_English#Local_Dublin_English|Local Dublin]]}}\n* {{homophones|en|carr|Carr|Karr}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɑː(ɹ)|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|:inh|enm:carre<id:cart>|id=wheeled vehicle}}\n{{inh+|en|enm|carre}}, borrowed from {{der|en|xno|carre}}, from {{der|en|fro-nor|-}} (compare {{cog|fro|char}}), from {{der|en|la|carrus||two-wheeled baggage wagon}}, from {{der|en|cel-gau|*karros}}, from {{der|en|cel-pro|*karros||wagon}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*ḱr̥sós||vehicle}}. {{dbt|en|carrus|horse}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|carr||archaic}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q1420}}A wheeled vehicle that moves independently, with at least three wheels, powered mechanically, steered by a driver and mostly for personal [[transportation]] but relatively smaller than a [[truck]]/[[lorry]] and a [[bus]].\n#: {{syn|en|auto|motorcar|vehicle|automobile|q4=US|motor|q5=Britain, colloquial|carriage|q6=obsolete|Thesaurus:automobile}}\n#: {{co|en|in a '''car'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|He drove his '''car''' to the theatre.}}\n#: {{ux|en| He was thinking about buying a brand new '''car'''.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|lyricist=Jordan Houston; Darnell Carlton; Paul Beauregard; Premro Smith; Marlon Goodwin; David Brown; Willie Hutchinson|passage=I'm a stunt; ride in the '''car''' with some bump in the trunk.|url=https://genius.com/Three-6-mafia-stay-fly-lyrics|title=Stay Fly|publisher=Sony BMG|year=2005|album=Most Known Unknown|artist=Three 6 Mafia (featuring Young Buck, 8 Ball, and MJG)}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=w:Edwin Black|title=Internal Combustion|chapter=1|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL4103950W|passage=If successful, Edison and Ford—in 1914—would move society away from the ever more expensive and then universally known killing hazards of gasoline '''cars''':&nbsp;[&hellip;]&thinsp;.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Sarah Holt|title=Verstappen wins Brazilian GP as Ferraris collide AND Gasly and Sainz claim first F1 podiums|magazine=w:CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/17/motorsport/formula-one-brazil-gp-verstappen-ferrari-collision-spt-intl/index.html|date=2019-11-17|passage=The race around the Interlagos circuit in São Paolo effectively became a 12-lap dash to the flag when Valtteri Bottas triggered the safety '''car''' after he pulled his Mercedes over with engine trouble.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Peter Valdes-Dapena|title=I hate to say it, but Ferrari’s new convertible is worth every penny|magazine=w:CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/09/19/success/ferrari-f8-spider-convertible-review/index.html|date=2020-09-19|passage=Then, of course, there are the '''cars''' themselves. The most valuable classic '''car''' ever sold at auction was a 1962 Ferrari 250 GTO that sold for more than $48 million in 2018. Of the top ten most valuable '''cars''' ever sold at auction, six are Ferraris.}}\n# {{lb|en|archaic}} A [[wheeled]] [[vehicle]], drawn by a [[horse]] or other animal.\n#* {{RQ:Marlowe Edward 2|year=1622|text=It shall suffice me to enioy your loue,<br>Which whiles I haue, I thinke my selfe as great,<br>As ''Caesar'' riding in the Romaine streete,<br>With captiue kings at his triumphant '''Carre'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Antony and Cleopatra|IV|8|text=He has deserved it [armour], were it carbuncled<br>Like holy Phoebus’ '''car'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Eddison Worm|page=19|passage=The Red Foliot sate in his '''car''' of polished ebony, drawn by six black horses with flowing manes and tails; before him went his musicians, pipers and minstrels doing their craft, and behind him fifty spearmen, weighed down with armour and ponderous shields that covered them from chin to toe.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1961|author={{w|Harry E. Wedeck}}|title=Dictionary of Aphrodisiacs|publisher=The Citadel Press|location=New York|page=87|passage=In a poem by Sappho, Aphrodite is represented as riding in a '''car''' drawn by sparrows.}}\n## {{lb|en|archaic}} A [[cart]].\n## {{lb|en|archaic}} A [[chariot]].\n## {{lb|en|UK|Birmingham|obsolete}} A four-wheeled [[cab]], as opposed to a (two-wheeled) [[Hansom cab]].\n# Any vehicle designed to run on rails, especially an unpowered one [[tow#Verb|towed]] by being connected to others.\n## {{senseid|en|Q208502}} {{lb|en|rail transport|chiefly|North America}} An unpowered unit in a [[railroad]] train, used to hold either passengers or cargo.\n##: {{syn|en|railcar<id:Q208502>|wagon|carriage}}\n##: {{ux|en|The conductor coupled the '''cars''' to the locomotive.}}\n## A similar vehicle used in special contexts, such as mines, quarries, and mills.<!--often construed as coordinate rather than hyponymous-->\n##: {{hypo|en|mill car|mine car|quarry car|skip car}}\n## {{lb|en|rail transport}} an individual vehicle, powered or unpowered, in a [[multiple unit]].\n##: {{ux|en|The 11:10 to London was operated by a 4-'''car''' diesel multiple unit.}}\n## {{senseid|en|passenger-carrying unit in a subway or elevated train, whether powered or not}}{{lb|en|rail transport}} A passenger-carrying unit in a [[subway]] or elevated train, whether powered or not.\n##: {{ux|en|From the frontmost '''car''' of the subway, he filmed the progress through the tunnel.}}\n## A [[rough]] [[unit]] of quantity approximating the amount which would fill a [[railroad]] car.\n##: {{syn|en|carload|wagonload}}\n##: {{ux|en|We ordered five hundred '''cars''' of gypsum.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1907|author=Texas Agricultural; Mechanical College System|journal=Bulletin| volume=93-117| page=5| passage=This market reports only one or two '''cars''' per day, selling by the hundred weight, and at a price a little lower than that of Indian corn.}}\n# The moving, load-carrying component of an [[elevator]] or other [[cable]]-drawn transport mechanism.\n#: {{ux|en|Fix the '''car''' of the express elevator - the door is sticking.}}\n# The passenger-carrying portion of certain [[amusement park]] rides, such as [[Ferris wheel]]s.\n#: {{syn|en|carriage}}\n#: {{ux|en|The most exciting part of riding a Ferris wheel is when your '''car''' goes over the top.}}\n# The part of an [[airship]], such as a [[balloon]] or [[dirigible]], which houses the passengers and control apparatus.\n#: {{syn|en|gondola|basket|q2=balloons only}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1850|author=[[w:John Wise (balloonist)|John Wise]]|title=[http://books.google.com/books?id=sfYOAAAAYAAJ A System of Aeronautics]|page=152\n|passage=Everything being apparently in readiness now, I stepped into the '''car''' of the balloon, {{...}}}}\n#* {{RQ:Doyle Lost World|passage=\"What about a''' car?'''\" \"The''' car '''will be my next care. I have already planned how it is to be made and attached. Meanwhile I will simply show you how capable my apparatus is of supporting the weight of each of us.\"}}\n# {{lb|en|sailing}} A sliding fitting that runs along a track.\n#* {{quote-book|en|1995|Ken Textor|The New Book of Sail Trim|https://www.google.com/books/edition/m/2JIbS0c1XPwC|201|isbn=9780924486814|On boats 25 feet or more, it is best to mount a mast '''car''' and track on the front of the mast so you can adjust the height of the pole above the deck.}}\n# {{lb|en|US}} A floating perforated box for living fish.\n# {{lb|en|US|prison slang}} A [[clique]] or [[gang]].\n# {{senseid|en|cat}} {{lb|en|internet|humorous}} {{deliberate misspelling of|en|cat}}.\n\n=====Hyponyms=====\n{{col3|en\n|amphibious car\n