{{tt|to|kā}}\n* Tumbuka: {{t|tum|galimoto}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|araba}}, {{tt+|tr|otomobil}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|سياره|tr=seyyare}}, {{t|ota|اوتوموبیل|tr=otomobil}}\n* Turkmen: {{tt|tk|maşyyn}}, {{tt+|tk|awtomaşyn}}, {{tt+|tk|awtomobil}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|авті́вка|f}}, {{tt+|uk|маши́на|f}}, {{tt+|uk|авто́|n}}, {{tt+|uk|автомобі́ль|m}}\n* Urdu: {{tt|ur|گاڑی|f}}, {{t|ur|کار|f}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt|ug|ئاپتوموبىل}}, {{tt|ug|ماشىنا}}\n* Uzbek: {{tt+|uz|avtomobil}}, {{tt+|uz|avtomashina}}, {{tt+|uz|mashina}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|xe hơi}}, {{tt+|vi|ô tô}}, {{tt+|vi|xe ô tô}}, {{tt+|vi|xe}} ({{tt+|vi|車}})\n* Vilamovian: {{tt|wym|wiöen}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|oto}}, {{t+|wa|vweteure}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|car|f}}\n* Xhosa: {{tt|xh|imoto}}\n* Yakut: {{tt|sah|массыына}}\n* Yiddish: {{tt|yi|אויטאָמאָביל|m}}, {{tt|yi|אויטאָ|m}}, {{tt|yi|מאַשין|f}}\n* Yoruba: {{tt|yo|ọkọ̀ ayọ́kẹ́lẹ́}}, {{tt|yo|mọ́tò}}, {{tt|yo|ọkọ̀}}\n* Zazaki: {{tt|zza|erewa}}\n* Zhuang: {{tt|za|giceh}}, {{tt|za|heiqci}}, {{tt|za|cihung}} {{q|dialectal}}\n* Zulu: {{tt+|zu|imoto}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|railway car, railroad carriage|carriage}}\n\n{{trans-see|passenger-carrying unit in a subway or elevated train, whether powered or not|carriage}}\n\n{{trans-top|moving, load-carrying component of an elevator}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|վագոն}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|cabina|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|吊艙|tr=diàocāng}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|kabina|f}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|elevatorstol|c}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|vagun}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|hissikori}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Kabine|f}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|θαλαμίσκος|m}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|תָּא|m|tr=ta}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|cabina|f}}\n* Ojibwe: {{tt|oj|akwaandawebizon}}, {{tt|oj|akwaandawaagan}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|kabina|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|elevador|m}} {{qualifier|passenger}}, {{tt|pt|monta-cargas|m}} {{qualifier|cargo}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|cabină|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|каби́на|f}}\n* Slovak: {{tt|sk|kabína|f}}\n* Swahili: {{tt+|sw|gari}}\n* Swedish: {{tt|sv|hisskorg|c}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|kabin}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Breton: {{t+check|br|karr-tan|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+check|eo|aŭto}}\n* Galician: {{t+check|gl|automóbil|m}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{t-check|gug|kóche}}, {{t-check|gug|mba'yru}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+check|id|mobil}}\n* Interlingua: {{t-check|ia|automobile}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+check|kmr|tirimpêl}}, {{t+check|kmr|erebe}}, {{t+check|kmr|seyare}}\n* Latin: {{t-check|la|carrus|m}}\n* Maltese: {{t+check|mt|karozza|f}}\n* Māori: {{t+check|mi|waka}}, {{t-check|mi|kā}}, {{t+check|mi|motokā}}\n* Swahili: {{qualifier|nc 5/6}} {{t+check|sw|gari}}\n* Tetum: {{t-check|tet|karreta}}\n* Thai: {{t+check|th|รถ|tr=rōht}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|en|bus}}\n* {{l|en|truck}}\n* {{l|en|van}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n[[File:Cons-cells.svg|thumb|Diagram for the list (42 69 613). The [[car]] of the first [[cons]] is 42, and the [[cdr]] points the next cons.]]\n{{acronym|en|[[content|'''c'''ontents]] of the [[address|'''a'''ddress]] part of [[register|'''r'''egister]] number}}. Note that it was based on original hardware and has no meaning today.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|programming}} The first part of a [[cons]] in [[Lisp]]. The first element of a list.\n#: {{ant|en|cdr}}\n#: {{holonyms|en|cons}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Matt Kaufmann; Panagiotis Manolios; J Strother Moore|title=Computer-aided reasoning: an approach|year=2000|passage=The elements of a list are the successive '''cars''' along the \"cdr chain.\" That is, the elements are the '''car''', the '''car''' of the cdr, the '''car''' of the cdr of the cdr, etc.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|cadr}}\n* {{l|en|caddr}}\n\n===Gallery===\n<gallery mode=packed>\nImage:TOYOTA FCHV 01.jpg|A hydrogen-powered '''car'''\nImage:Train wagons 0834.jpg|Freight '''cars'''\nImage:RandenTrain.jpg|A self-propelled passenger '''car'''\nImage:Ferris wheel - melbourne show 2005.jpg|Ferris wheel '''cars'''\nImage:Traveller (sailing).jpg|'''Car''' on a sailboat\nImage:ZeppelinLZ127b.jpg|'''Car''' of a Zeppelin\n</gallery>\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Century 1911}}\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=acr|ARC|CRA|RAC|RCA|acr-|arc|arc-|rac-}}\n\n{{cln|en|3-letter words}}\n{{C|en|Automobiles|Vehicles}}\n\n==Aromanian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|rup|caru}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|rup|la|carrus}}, from {{der|rup|cel-gau|*karros}}. Compare {{cog|ro|car}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|rup|noun|g=n|plural|cari}}\n\n# [[chariot]]\n# ox-[[cart]]\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|rup|cãrutsã}}/{{l|rup|carotsã}}\n* {{l|rup|cãrutsar}}\n* {{l|rup|caretã}}\n* {{l|rup|cherã}}\n\n==Äynu==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|aib|noun}}\n\n# [[mouth]]\n\n==Catalan==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|ca|la|cārus}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{ca-IPA|carr|bal=ca<q:Mallorca, Menorca>,carr<q:Ibiza>}}<!-- per GDLC, DCVB -->\n* {{rhymes|ca|aɾ|s=1}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{ca-adj}}\n\n# [[expensive]]\n#: {{syn|ca|alt|costós}}\n#: {{ant|ca|barat}}\n# {{lb|ca|poetic}} [[dear]]\n#: {{syn|ca|estimat|amat|apreciat}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{inh+|ca|la|quārē||how; why}}. Compare {{cog|fr|car}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{ca-IPA|carr<!--|bal=?-->}}<!-- FIXME: pronun for this meaning not given in DCVB -->\n* {{rhymes|ca|aɾ|s=1}}\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|ca|conjunction}}\n\n# {{lb|ca|archaic}} [[as]], [[since]], [[because]], [[for]]\n#: {{syn|ca|perquè}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{bor+|ca|gkm|κάροιον|t=yard, spar}}, from {{der|ca|grc|κεραίᾱ}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{ca-IPA|carr}}<!-- per GDLC, DCVB -->\n* {{rhymes|ca|aɾ|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{ca-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|ca|nautical}} [[foreyard]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:ca:DCVB}}\n\n==Czech==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|cs|cu|цѣсарь}}, from {{der|cs|sla-pro|*cěsařь}}, from a {{der|cs|gem}} language, from {{der|cs|gem-pro|*kaisaraz}}, from {{der|cs|la|Caesar}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{cs-IPA}}\n* {{hyphenation|cs|car}}\n* {{rhymes|cs|ar|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{cs-noun|m-an}}\n\n# [[tsar]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{cs-ndecl|m.an.nomplové}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|cs|carský|carevna|carevič|Cařihrad|carismus|carství}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:cs:PSJC}}\n* {{R:cs:SSJC}}\n\n{{C|cs|Heads of state|Monarchy}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|Fr-car.ogg}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-GrandCelinien-car.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Paris>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-car.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Poslovitch-car.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-car.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Jérémy-Günther-Heinz Jähnick-car.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Somain>>)}}\n* {{rhymes|fr|aʁ|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|fr|fro|quer||as, since, because, for}}, from {{der|fr|la|quare|quārē|how; why}}. Compare {{cog|ca|car}}.\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|fr|conjunction}}\n\n# [[as]], [[since]], [[because]], [[for]]\n#: {{ux|fr|J’ai ouvert mon parapluie '''car''' il pleuvait.|I opened my umbrella '''because''' it was raining.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|fr|year=c. 1656–1662|author=Blaise Pascal|title=''Dossier de travail'' - Fragment n° 10 / 35|journal=Pensées|trans-journal=Thoughts|passage='''Car''' dans la création de l’homme Adam en était le témoin et le dépositaire de la promesse du sauveur qui devait naître de la femme, lorsque les hommes étaient encore si proches de la Création qu’ils ne pouvaient avoir oublié leur création et leur chute.|t='''For''' in the creation of man, Adam was the witness and the depositary of the promise of the saviour who would be born of woman, when the men were still so close to the Creation that they could not have forgotten their creation and their fall.|url=http://www.penseesdepascal.fr/I/I10-moderne.php}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n{{m|fr|car}} is a coordinating conjunction while {{m|fr|parce que}} is a subordinating conjunction.\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|fr|parce que}} {{qualifier|in some contexts}} {{attention|fr|Someone left a comment saying \"This is not a perfect synonym, a usage note by a native speaker would be good\"}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nBorrowed from {{bor|fr|en|car}}, itself borrowed from {{der|fr|xno|-}} and the {{der|fr|fro-nor|car}}, variant of {{der|fr|fro|char}}. {{doublet|fr|char}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# a single-decked long-distance, or privately hired, {{l|en|bus}}, a [[coach]]\n#: {{syn|fr|autocar}}\n#: {{uxi|fr|Les élèves vont à l’école en '''car'''.|The pupils go to school by '''coach'''.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|fr\n|aéro-car\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:Larousse}}\n* {{R:fr:Littré}}\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|fr|arc}}\n\n{{cln|fr|coordinating conjunctions}}\n{{C|fr|Vehicles}}\n\n==Interlingua==\n\n===Adjective===\n{{ia-adj}}\n\n# [[dear]]; [[beloved]]; [[cherished]]\n# [[expensive]]\n\n==Irish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|ga|ine-pro|*keh₂-}}\nFrom {{inh|ga|sga|caraid}}, from {{inh|ga|cel-pro|*karāti||to love}}, from {{der|ga|ine-pro|*keh₂-||to desire, wish}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ga|/kaɾˠ/}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{ga-verb|pres=~ann|fut=~faidh|vn=carthain|pp=~tha}}\n\n# to [[love]]\n# be [[devote|devoted]] to\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{ga-conj-1a|c|a|r|broad|vn=carthain}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|ga|gráigh}}\n\n===Mutation===\n{{ga-mut}}\n\n{{C|ga|Love}}\n\n==Lombard==\n\n===Etymology===\nAkin to {{cog|it|caro}}, from Latin ''[[carus]]''.\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|lmo|adjective}}\n\n# [[dear]]\n\n==Manx==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|gv|ine-pro|*(s)ker-|id=turn}}\nFrom {{der|gv|sga|cor||act of putting}}, verbal noun of {{m|sga|fo·ceird||to put}}.<ref>{{R:DIL|12406|head=1 cor}}</ref> Cognate with {{cog|ga|cor}} and {{cog|gd|car}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|gv|/kar/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{gv-noun|m|khyr|-}}\n\n# [[twist]], [[turn]]; a period of time\n#: {{uxi|gv|'''car''' ny bleeaney|t=all the year round}}\n#: {{uxi|gv|'''car''' y touree|t=all summer}}\n#: {{uxi|gv|'''car''' y voghrey|t=all morning}}\n#: {{uxi|gv|'''car''' yn astyr|t=all evening}}\n#* {{quote-book|gv|year=1814|title=Aght Giare|author=John Clague|page=37\n|passage=''Q. Cre t’ou toiggal liorish yn Chargys? <br>A. Trostey ’sy niarragh '''car da-eed laa''' roish y chaisht.''\n|t=Q. What do you mean by Lent? <br>A. The spring fast '''of forty Days''' before Easter.\n}}\n#* {{RQ:gv:Bible|Isaiah|18|6|passage=''Bee ad faagit cooidjagh da eeanlee ny sleityn, as da maase y vagheragh;<br>nee ny eeanlee tannaghtyn orroo '''car y touree''', as maase y vagheragh '''car y yeuree'''.''|t=They will all be left to the mountain birds of prey and to the wild animals;<br>the birds will feed on them '''all summer''', the wild animals '''all winter'''.}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nUsed adverbially to mean  'throughout [a certain time]', but not with {{l|gv|laa}} or {{l|gv|oie}}.\n\n====See also====\n{{col|gv|fey-ny-laa|fud-ny-hoie|carr}}\n\n===Mutation===\n{{gv-mut-cons|c|ar}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Middle French==\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|frm|conjunction}}\n\n# [[for]] (because)\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|fr|car}}\n\n==Occitan==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|oc|pro}}, from {{inh|oc|la|carus|cārus}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|oc|LL-Q14185 (oci)-Davidgrosclaude-car.wav|a=Béarn}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{oc-adj}}\n\n# [[dear]]\n# [[expensive]]\n\n==Old French==\n\n===Noun===\n{{fro-noun|m}}\n\n# {{alt form of|fro|char}}\n\n[[Category:Old Northern French]]\n\n==Piedmontese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|pms|/kar/}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|pms|adjective}}\n\n# [[dear]]\n\n==Polish==\n{{wp|pl:}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pl-pr|a=Pl-car.ogg|las=#}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|pl|:bor|ru:царь|text=+|tree=1}} {{dbt|pl|cesarz|cezar|kajzer}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{pl-noun|m-pr}}\n\n# {{lb|pl|historical}} [[czar]], [[tsar]], [[tzar]] {{gl|title of the former emperors of Russia}}\n#: {{syn|pl|batiuszka|q1=colloquial}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{pl-decl-noun-m-pr|||carowie}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|pl|title=adjectives|antycarski|carowy|carski}}\n{{col|pl|title=nouns|carat|carewicz|carewna|carobójca|carobójstwo|carowa|carówna|carstwo|caryca|caryzm|carzyk}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nSee {{m|pl|czar}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{pl-noun|m-in}}\n\n# {{lb|pl|Lasovia}} {{alt form|pl|czar}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pl:WSJP}}\n* {{R:pl:PWN}}\n* {{R:pl:Matusiak:1880|cary|171}}\n\n{{C|pl|Heads of state|Male people|Monarchy|Nobility|Russia}}\n\n==Romagnol==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|rgn|la|carrus||wagon; cart}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{rgn-IPA|rf=1|r=1|vu=1|'|c|à|r}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{rgn-noun|m|chër}} {{tlb|rgn|V}}\n\n# {{l|en|wagon}}, {{l|en|cart}}\n\n==Romanian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ro|[kar]}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|ro|la|carrus}}, from {{der|ro|cel-gau|*karros}}. Sense 3 is influenced by {{der|ro|fr|char}} and/or {{der|ro|it|carro armato}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{ro-noun|n|care}}\n\n# [[cart]]\n# [[chariot]]\n# {{lb|ro|outdated}} [[tank]] (military vehicle)\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ro-noun-n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|ro|căruță}}\n* {{l|ro|cărare}}\n* {{l|ro|căra}}\n* {{l|ro|caretă}}\n* {{l|ro|încărca}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|ro|verb form}}\n\n# {{verb form of|ro|căra||1s|pres|ind//sub}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{inh|ro|la|caries}} or {{m|la|carius}}. {{doublet|ro|carie}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|ro|cariu}} {{q|dated}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{ro-noun|m|cari}}\n\n# {{senseid|ro|beetle}} [[death-watch beetle]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ro-noun-m}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nFrom {{bor|ro|rom|kar}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{ro-noun|m|car}}\n\n# {{lb|ro|vulgar|_|slang}} [[dick]], [[cock]] {{gloss|the penis}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ro-noun-m}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|ro|cocar}}\n* {{l|ro|carici}}\n\n{{C|ro|Vehicles|Bostrichiform beetles}}\n\n==Scottish Gaelic==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|gd|sga|cor||act of putting}}, verbal noun of {{m|sga|foceird|fo·ceird|to put}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|gd|/kʰaɾ/|ref={{R:Mac Gill-Fhinnein:1966}}}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{gd-noun|g=m|gen=cuir|pl=caran}}\n\n# [[job]]\n# [[twist]], [[turn]]\n# [[trick]] {{rfex|gd}}\n# [[bit]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|gd|aig a' char as lugha}}\n* {{l|gd|aig a' char as miosa}}\n* {{l|gd|cuir car de}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|gd|adverb}}\n\n# [[somewhat]], [[quite]], [[rather]]\n#: {{ux|gd|Tha thu '''car''' fadalach.|inline=1|You're somewhat late.}}\n#: {{ux|gd|Thàinig an stòiridh gu ceann '''car''' obann.|inline=1|The story came to an end somewhat abruptly.}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|gd|caran}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|size=smaller}}\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|sh|sla-pro|*cěsařь}}, {{m|sla-pro|*cьsarь}}, from a {{der|sh|gem}} language, from {{der|sh|gem-pro|*kaisaraz}}, from {{der|sh|la|Caesar}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sh-IPA|cȁr}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sh-noun|cȁr|m-an}}\n\n# [[czar]], [[emperor]], [[monarch]]\n#: {{uxi|sh|Podajte '''caru''' carevo, a Bogu Božje.|Give the Emperor what belongs to the Emperor and God what belongs to God.}}\n#* {{quote-book|sh|title=Baš-Čelik|year=1971|location=Belgrade|author=Branko B. Radičević|page=1|passage=Bijaše jedan '''car''', i imađaše tri sina i tri ćerke.|translation=There once was a '''tsar''' and he had three daughters and three sons.}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sh-decl-noun\n|cȁr|cȁrevi\n|cȁra|cȁrēvā\n|cȁru|cȁrevima\n|cȁra|cȁreve\n|cȁre / cȁru ''(rare)''|cȁrevi\n|cȁru|cȁrevima\n|cȁrem|cȁrevima\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|sh|carevina|cȁrevina}}\n* {{l|sh|carica|cȁrica}}\n* {{l|sh|carina|cȁrina}}\n* {{l|sh|carstvo|cȃrstvo}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:sh:HJP|f11jWhg%3D}}\n\n{{C|sh|Heads of state|Monarchy}}\n\n==Slovene==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|sl|sh|car|cȁr}}, from {{der|sl|sla-pro|*cěsařь}}, from a {{der|sl|gem}} language, from {{der|sl|gem-pro|*kaisaraz}}, from {{der|sl|la|Caesar}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sl-IPA|cār}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sl-noun|cār|m-an|f=caríca|f2=cārinja}}\n\n# [[tsar]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{sl-decl-noun-m|cár|cárj}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|sl|cesar|césar}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:sl:Fran}}\n\n{{C|sl|Heads of state|Monarchy}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|es|la|quare|quārē|why}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|es|conjunction}}\n\n# {{lb|es|archaic}} [[because]]\n#: {{syn|es|porque|ca<l:archaic>}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:es:DRAE}}\n\n==Volapük==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|vo|[tʃar]}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{vo-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|vo|weapon}} [[bow]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{vo-decl-noun}}\n\n{{C|vo|Weapons}}\n\n==Welsh==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|cy|wlm|carr}}, from {{inh|cy|cel-bry-pro|*karr}}, from {{inh|cy|cel-pro|*karros}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|cy|/kar/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{cy-noun|m|ceir}}\n\n# [[#English|car]]\n# {{lb|cy|obsolete}} [[cart]], [[wagon]]\n#: {{syn|cy|cart|cert|trol|men}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|cy|allwedd car||car key}}\n* {{l|cy|carwden||backband}}\n* {{l|cy|rhif car||registration number}}\n* {{l|cy|sêl cist car||car boot sale}}\n\n===Mutation===\n{{cy-mut}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:cy:GyrA|2=car}}\n* {{R:cy:Gweiadur}}\n* {{R:cy:GPC}}\n\n{{c|cy|Vehicles}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|yol|enm|carre}}, from {{der|yol|xno|carre}}, from {{der|yol|la|carra}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|yol|/kar/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|yol|noun}}\n\n# [[#English|car]]\n#: {{syn|yol|truckle}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1927|chapter=ZONG OF TWI MAARKEET MOANS|line=6|page=129|title=THE ANCIENT DIALECT OF THE BARONIES OF FORTH AND BARGY, COUNTY WEXFORD|passage=An awi gome her egges wi a wheel an '''car''' taape,|translation=And away went her eggs, with the '''car''' overset.}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Browne 1927|page=129}}\n\n==Zazaki==\n\n===Proper noun===\n{{zza-noun|g=m}}\n\n# [[god]]"}}